about what to say tonight

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:50.560
to introduce Jim, I
remembered something

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:53.020
that Fred Allen said
about radio.

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:55.590
Fred Allen, great
comedian and satirist

00:01:55.590 --> 00:01:59.060
of what we call the Golden Age
of Radio in the 30s and 40s

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:03.950
who never quite recovered
from the assent of television

00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:09.230
in the 50s had this to say, "The
radio listeners saw nothing.

00:02:09.230 --> 00:02:11.530
He had to use imagination.

00:02:11.530 --> 00:02:13.310
It was possible for
each individual

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:15.120
to enjoy the same
program according

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:18.070
to his intellectual level
and his mental capacity.

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:20.660
With the high-cost of living and
the many problems facing them

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:22.920
in the modern world, all
the poor man had left was

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:24.340
his imagination.

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:28.150
Television has taken
that away from him."

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:33.250
So, obviously he didn't
think too much of television.

00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:35.290
I'm okay with television.

00:02:35.290 --> 00:02:36.700
I'm sure you are too,

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.150
but a really interesting thing
happened about the same time

00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:43.550
that Fred Allen wrote that as
television was becoming ascended

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:49.200
which is that the portable
tape recorder became something

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:54.390
that was in reach, not to
everybody, but it was something

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:57.290
that if you thought that
what's you wanted to do

00:02:57.290 --> 00:02:59.850
and you save some money for
a while, you could get one

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:02.870
and you could go out in world
and record what you wanted

00:03:02.870 --> 00:03:06.850
and bring it back and find a
way to program it to present it

00:03:06.850 --> 00:03:10.340
and people did that, beyond
the obvious applications

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:13.270
for recording music and
political speeches and things

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:16.970
like that, innovators like Tony
Schwartz whose collection is

00:03:16.970 --> 00:03:21.990
here at the Library of Congress,
went out and collected sounds

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:28.390
and thoughts and dreams, and
gave them back to the world

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:31.020
as a means of not only

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:33.590
of communication but
also inspiration.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:37.530
And I see tonight's guest,
Jim Metzner very much

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:40.470
in the tradition of
innovators like Tony Schwartz

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:43.390
and Jim you actually,
you knew Tony Schwartz.

