&gt;&gt; Sticks, for beating
those sticks together.

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:40.880
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Maybe.

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:42.180
What?

00:15:42.180 --> 00:15:43.480
&gt;&gt; It sounded like a
child wearing flip-flops.

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:44.780
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: My man.

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:46.080
&gt;&gt; Flip-flops.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:47.380
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Close.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:48.680
You get, you get the prize

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:52.030
but flip-flops would have
a, the rhythm was right.

00:15:52.030 --> 00:15:53.730
So, you have, you
got the rhythm part.

00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:56.810
It's the rhythm of a
child, in fact, a girl.

00:15:56.810 --> 00:16:00.210
It's the rhythm some part
of the as you hear it,

00:16:00.210 --> 00:16:03.700
you say of course yes it's
a child's, a girl is running

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:05.000
but what does she
have on her feet?

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.300
It ain't flip-flops.

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:07.600
&gt;&gt; Clogs.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:08.900
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Bingo.

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:10.200
You got it.

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:11.500
Clogs. So, she's running,

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:14.460
so I mean the sounds
are telling us that.

00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:19.180
We just, you just have to, you
know, decipher it in a way.

00:16:19.180 --> 00:16:21.260
I mean, it's speaking
to us without words.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:24.650
Now these have been
all relatively subtle,

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:28.580
nondescript soundscapes,
but there are sounds

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:30.890
that basically demand
our attention.

00:16:30.890 --> 00:16:35.030
They grab you by the ears
and they say, "Remember me.

00:16:35.030 --> 00:16:36.330
Record me."

00:16:36.330 --> 00:16:38.050
And this is what
sound recordists,

00:16:38.050 --> 00:16:40.260
guys like Matt was saying

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:44.890
like Tony Schwartz
did or Alan Lomax did.

00:16:44.890 --> 00:16:47.930
We attune to the world,
take these impressions

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:51.210
and share the world of
sound in the same way

00:16:51.210 --> 00:16:54.210
that photographers
take impressions

00:16:54.210 --> 00:16:56.060
of the visual landscape.

00:16:56.060 --> 00:17:00.740
Well, Minor White and I know
there are some folks here

00:17:00.740 --> 00:17:04.960
who know Minor was
a photographer

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:09.520
who my very good friend who is
in this audience, Mr. Lee Ewing

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:16.250
and I many moons ago in
1972, were Minor's assistants

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:20.350
on a photographic trip that
he took across the country

00:17:20.350 --> 00:17:22.390
and it was an amazing trip.

00:17:22.390 --> 00:17:24.460
We hung out with Ansel Adams,

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:26.550
Minor co-developed
the zone system

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:29.070
of photography with Ansel.

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:33.780
Well, we would spend the whole
day photographing things.

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:36.730
We would be photographing
rock walls you remember?

00:17:36.730 --> 00:17:40.180
And Minor had this big camera
and we had these little Leicas

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:42.660
and he would be there and wall
would be full of moss and we,

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:45.850
he would just be standing there
photographing this rock wall

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:48.830
and people would come by
sometimes and you'd sort

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:50.500
of see a guy photographing
a rock wall

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:53.720
and then some guy would come up
and maybe pluck up his courage

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:58.230
and saying, "You
photographing a rock wall?"

00:17:58.230 --> 00:18:00.200
And we go, "Yeah."

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:02.160
That's what we've been up to.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:07.750
But one day Minor
came to me and said,

00:18:07.750 --> 00:18:09.810
and he had a very deep voice.

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:13.170
I don't know if can do it, but
it was something like "Well,

00:18:13.170 --> 00:18:19.780
Jim something out
there is waiting for me

00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:26.950
to record it, to photograph it.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:29.960
Something out there is waiting
for me to photograph it.

00:18:29.960 --> 00:18:35.800
I don't know what it is,
but it will find me."

00:18:35.800 --> 00:18:42.810
And, I spent the better
part of my life recording

00:18:42.810 --> 00:18:47.930
and Minor's words have come back
to me because there are sounds

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:52.660
that really find you,
had it not been for you,

00:18:52.660 --> 00:18:58.680
it would have never have been
remembered or heard or shared.

00:18:58.680 --> 00:19:01.280
It would be like that tree
that fell in the forest

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:03.890
and nobody was there to hear it.

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:10.320
This is one of those sounds and
it was completely unexpected

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:13.780
and I'll give you a little bit
of prep; first of all, this is,

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:20.960
well I went to Brazil
in 75 and this is

00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:23.390
like the first thing I
recorded it was a little town

00:19:23.390 --> 00:19:26.240
of [foreign word spoken]
which is in Salvador in Bahia,

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:31.100
the heart of Brazil and
there was this church service

00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:34.730
that was just ending
and you'll hear

00:19:34.730 --> 00:19:39.410
as the service begins the
choir master is having a slight

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:43.000
conversation with the organist
and everything that you're

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:48.540
about to hear was
exactly as it happened.

00:19:48.540 --> 00:19:49.840
There's no editing.

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:51.140
There's no mixing.

00:19:51.140 --> 00:19:54.010
What you hear is what
I got in this moment

00:19:54.010 --> 00:19:59.270
and then the recording just sort
of I was carrying my recorder

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:02.090
so we sort of followed
the crowd out,

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:08.510
the congregation
out into the street.

