00:23:02.200 --> 00:23:03.560
They didn't disappoint.

00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:09.560
Well to witness and
record a moment like that,

00:23:09.560 --> 00:23:12.300
you really feel like
you've been given a gift

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:18.570
and you become very still,
attentive to the sound

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:21.930
and that's partly technical

00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:24.700
because if there any
sound recorders out there,

00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:27.000
there are people here I'm
sure who record sounds,

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.670
Tom we know you're
one of them, yeah.

00:23:29.670 --> 00:23:33.460
But you know that if you make
too much noise you just ruined

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:34.760
your recording.

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:37.990
So, you have to be still
so it's partly technical,

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:43.600
but really every
act of listening,

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:50.290
really listening demands this
quality of attention doesn't it?

00:23:50.290 --> 00:23:55.440
It reminds us that like the
world that we're listening

00:23:55.440 --> 00:23:59.900
to which is alive,
we too are alive.

00:24:01.340 --> 00:24:05.320
Right now the vibration
of my voice travelling

00:24:05.320 --> 00:24:08.520
through this room is
reaching you through your skin

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:15.170
into your bones and it may be
subtle, but right now we are

00:24:15.170 --> 00:24:20.100
in resonance and as an
experiment we could even try now

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:22.130
if you would like to maybe come

00:24:22.130 --> 00:24:24.890
into resonance a
little bit more.

00:24:24.890 --> 00:24:29.280
There's an exercise
that my friend Tim Hill

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:31.660
who does [foreign
word spoken] singing.

00:24:31.660 --> 00:24:37.170
He was singing that when you do
it you actually accentuate some

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:40.950
of the tones of your voice
which are in all of our voices

00:24:40.950 --> 00:24:42.950
to bring out two tones
at the same time.

00:24:42.950 --> 00:24:44.250
I'm not saying we're going

00:24:44.250 --> 00:24:47.170
to start singing
[inaudible] throat chant now,

00:24:47.170 --> 00:24:51.170
but as an experiment
we're going to go

00:24:51.170 --> 00:24:52.800
through a series
of vowels together.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:56.940
We'll find a note and
we're going to say the word

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.650
"why" except we're
going to really,

00:24:59.650 --> 00:25:02.210
if you want to participate
why not, I mean you know,

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:05.710
close your eyes no one, no one
will see you, and we're going

00:25:05.710 --> 00:25:10.470
to say "why" but it's going to
go w-i-e and we'll pick a note,

00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:12.660
I don't know, let's
somebody find a note,

00:25:12.660 --> 00:25:14.720
ooo is that a good note for you?

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:19.000
Ooo, so oo-why, you ready?

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:34.730
Ooo-i-e. Now we're
going to go backwards,

00:25:34.730 --> 00:25:37.850
ee-i-ow, ee-i-otherwise.

00:25:37.850 --> 00:25:53.990
Even in that you could hear that
just the taste of the overtones,

00:25:53.990 --> 00:26:02.110
the parts of our voice that
are there all the time,

00:26:02.110 --> 00:26:05.190
but if you go and
you try that at home,

00:26:05.190 --> 00:26:06.670
you don't have to
be a professional.

00:26:06.670 --> 00:26:11.180
You can try this at home
in a very reflective place

00:26:11.180 --> 00:26:14.020
like your car or the shower,
try that and you'll start

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:16.710
to hear the overtones
that are present

00:26:16.710 --> 00:26:19.940
in your voice and
in every sound.

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:22.530
There are just certain places

00:26:22.530 --> 00:26:26.200
where the environment makes
it a little bit more possible

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:28.300
for you to hear them.

00:26:28.300 --> 00:26:31.770
So, right now whether we're
making sound together or not,

00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:38.820
we're all breathing together
in a silent chorus creating

00:26:38.820 --> 00:26:43.670
at the same time
with our listening,

00:26:43.670 --> 00:26:47.410
that we're doing together
by default, an atmosphere

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:54.110
of listening and if you don't
believe that, tell me the truth.

00:26:54.110 --> 00:26:57.660
If you're in a conversation
with somebody,

00:26:57.660 --> 00:27:00.440
can't you tell intuitively
whether

00:27:00.440 --> 00:27:02.860
that person's listening
to you or not?

00:27:02.860 --> 00:27:04.160
You know it.

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:05.460
Alright, sometimes
it's body language,

00:27:05.460 --> 00:27:08.360
sometimes it's just this you
know when somebody's tuning out

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:10.500
and you know even better
when they're tuning in.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:13.530
Now, what is that all about?

00:27:13.530 --> 00:27:14.830
So, when you have a group

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:19.800
of people listening
together we are creating

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:23.720
between us an amplified kind

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:27.280
of listening that's maybe
only possible when a group

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:30.660
of people are together listening
on behalf of something else

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:32.960
and nay actor, any
performer knows that.

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:35.080
You get a good crowd and you
say, "Wow, great crowd tonight"

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:37.220
and it helps brings up
the level of the music.

00:27:37.220 --> 00:27:41.280
Why? Well, maybe the
performer was knowing that he

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:45.940
or she was being listened to,
it's like a feedback loop.

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:51.380
Well, we're not alone, we
have lots of other entities

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:54.790
on the planet that are engaged
in the process of listening.

00:27:54.790 --> 00:27:57.710
We've got company,
a lot of company.

00:27:57.710 --> 00:28:02.300
So, over the course of my career
I've interviewed many scientists

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:04.640
and we do have scientists,
there are scientists

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:09.140
in the house tonight and I've
interviewed, I don't know,

00:28:09.140 --> 00:28:12.390
hundreds maybe even thousands,
really thousands of scientists,

00:28:12.390 --> 00:28:16.310
but hundreds of bio-acousticians
whose job it is to sort

00:28:16.310 --> 00:28:21.290
of monitor the pulse of the
creatures there are in the world

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:23.400
and you get this sense,
I've gotten this sense

00:28:23.400 --> 00:28:27.230
after interviewing
them, that my golly it's

00:28:27.230 --> 00:28:31.370
as if every living thing
on earth is some form

00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:35.580
of receptivity or
listening or communication

00:28:35.580 --> 00:28:39.580
and we humans are only privy
to small portion of that.

00:28:39.580 --> 00:28:44.820
So, for example, bats and rats
are in the ultrasonic range

00:28:44.820 --> 00:28:46.910
above the range of
human hearing.

00:28:46.910 --> 00:28:49.970
Elephants are infrasonic,
they're below the range

00:28:49.970 --> 00:28:52.620
of human hearing and
they actually communicate

00:28:52.620 --> 00:28:54.320
to each other.

00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:58.850
Yeast cells actually vibrate.

00:28:58.850 --> 00:29:03.430
Leaf hoppers which are
an insect, I promised,

00:29:03.430 --> 00:29:07.000
I promised you that
there would be some wild

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:10.150
and crazy animal sounds,
this is one of them.

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:12.900
Leaf hoppers make a
sound to each other

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:18.100
that we humans can't hear,
but if you were a leaf hopper

00:29:18.100 --> 00:29:21.360
and were on the surface
of a plant you'd be tuning

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:22.660
into these vibrations.

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:24.580
Well, somebody had
the very clever idea,

00:29:24.580 --> 00:29:26.420
it was a Japanese
scientist I believe,

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:29.850
had the very clever idea taking
what's called a transducer

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:32.420
which just translates
vibrations to sound.

00:29:32.420 --> 00:29:34.590
In fact, he used a
phonograph believe it or not,

00:29:34.590 --> 00:29:38.890
he stuck it on the plant,
the substrate of the plant,

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:44.180
the mass of the plant, and these
are the highly amplified sounds

00:29:44.180 --> 00:29:49.510
of leaf hoppers, tiny insects.

00:29:49.510 --> 00:30:34.140
[ Insect Sounds ]

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:35.440
That's two of them.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:40.160
That's the call and
response of the leaf hoppers,

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:45.550
it was the mate calling on
"who" that was the mate.

00:30:45.550 --> 00:30:47.110
So, transduce sound.

00:30:47.110 --> 00:30:51.300
If you want an example of
transduce sound you could

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:55.660
if you put your palm of your
hand against your ear and tap

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:58.660
on your elbow, you
can hear that.

00:30:58.660 --> 00:30:59.960
Do you hear that?

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:01.840
Now how are you hearing it?

00:31:01.840 --> 00:31:03.140
If you tap with your knuckles

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:05.360
on your elbow you're
hearing it right?

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:06.660
So, how are you hearing that?

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:08.250
&gt;&gt; Bone-to-bone vibrations.

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:09.550
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Pardon?

00:31:09.550 --> 00:31:10.850
&gt;&gt; Bone-to-bone.

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:12.150
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Bone-to-bone,
yeah.

00:31:12.150 --> 00:31:15.430
It's being conducted transduced
through the same principle.

00:31:15.430 --> 00:31:18.760
So, of course, there
are plenty of insects

00:31:18.760 --> 00:31:22.270
that we do hear all
the time like cicadas

00:31:22.270 --> 00:31:25.720
and crickets they are
among the voices of nature

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:30.420
that we hear many evenings
along with amphibians

00:31:30.420 --> 00:31:32.310
and this is a taste

00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:37.050
of a nighttime chorus
in Brazil's Pantanal.

00:31:37.050 --> 00:31:40.650
It's actually not only Brazil,
there's a number of countries

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:46.740
around this the largest
wetland in Brazil, excuse me,

00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:50.640
the largest wetland in the world
of which Brazil is just one

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:53.650
of the countries
in the, on the map.

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:56.600
I think Paraguay is another
and I'm trying to remember,

00:31:56.600 --> 00:31:58.040
there are four countries
in the Pantanal.

00:31:58.040 --> 00:31:59.830
Anybody know off the
top of their head?

00:31:59.830 --> 00:32:02.540
I don't remember what they are.

00:32:02.540 --> 00:32:03.840
Largest wetland in the world

00:32:03.840 --> 00:32:08.070
and at night the
chorus sounds like this.

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:11.790
Now, when we're listening
to it you might try

00:32:11.790 --> 00:32:18.350
as maybe an exercise
or just an experiment,

00:32:18.350 --> 00:32:21.540
to hear the spatiality
of the sound.

00:32:21.540 --> 00:32:24.360
In other words, well there's
a different sound over here,

00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:29.750
there's three sounds are in 3D;
we're getting a spatial effect

00:32:29.750 --> 00:32:34.700
of where the different sounds
are and sounds also have a kind

00:32:34.700 --> 00:32:36.750
of a texture and they
may even have a kind

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:40.780
of an image not the
necessarily the image

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:43.470
of what it is that's making
that sound, but the image

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:45.930
of the sound itself
that could be produced

00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:51.500
in your mind as you hear it, so.

00:32:52.510 --> 00:33:52.400
[ Insect Sounds ]

00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:53.880
Any images come to mind?

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:55.510
Anybody want to?

00:33:55.510 --> 00:33:58.510
Well, what do you think
of when you hear that?

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:04.840
[ Insect Sounds ]

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:08.150
I don't know why, but
there's something,

00:34:08.150 --> 00:34:32.680
kind of the sounds remind
me of the surface sort

00:34:32.680 --> 00:34:37.030
of like the walls of
the ceiling, you know,

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:42.530
there's something rough and
amazing about it [inaudible].

00:34:42.530 --> 00:34:50.390
Well, most mornings there are
a few other sounds of insects

00:34:50.390 --> 00:34:55.070
and amphibians and insects
cross-fading with the sounds

00:34:55.070 --> 00:34:57.280
of a dawn chorus of birds.

00:34:57.280 --> 00:35:06.370
This dawn chorus was
recorded in the Grampians

00:35:06.370 --> 00:35:09.430
which is a park outside of
Melbourne West of Melbourne,

00:35:09.430 --> 00:35:13.450
Australia and it's a park
run by Aboriginal peoples

00:35:13.450 --> 00:35:17.940
and as I was recording this the
crack of dawn, I was surrounded

00:35:17.940 --> 00:35:21.820
by birds and many other
creatures including kangaroos

00:35:21.820 --> 00:35:25.680
which you won't hear, they
weren't making any sounds.

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:29.440
I doing think kangaroos make
a sound, but just the fact

00:35:29.440 --> 00:35:31.410
that knowing that
there were kangaroos

00:35:31.410 --> 00:35:32.710
around I think is cool.

00:35:32.710 --> 00:35:37.570
Anyway, this is one of my
favorite dawn choruses and,

00:35:37.570 --> 00:35:40.430
but another experiment of
another kind of listening

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:48.210
to imagine you can try this also
with a musical sound as well,

00:35:48.210 --> 00:35:53.650
as you're listening try
to imagine a mountain

00:35:53.650 --> 00:35:57.910
or visualize a mountain of
sound the lows are at the bottom

00:35:57.910 --> 00:35:59.700
of a mountain and the
highs are at the top,

00:35:59.700 --> 00:36:02.920
and as you're listening it's
as if you become the mountain

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:06.070
and you're sort of [audio
issues], you're sort of reaching

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:09.340
for the higher notes and that
even affects your posture

00:36:09.340 --> 00:36:13.570
so that there's a kind of a
posture, a more erect posture

00:36:13.570 --> 00:36:14.870
of listening or a
posture that's conducive

00:36:14.870 --> 00:36:16.170
to listening especially
reaching for those highs.

00:36:16.170 --> 00:36:17.470
This exercise I didn't invent,
it's something that belongs

00:36:17.470 --> 00:36:19.040
to Alfred Tomatis' work in the
Listening Center and he someone

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:20.630
who spent his life, who spent
is life studying and listening.

00:36:20.630 --> 00:36:22.160
Anyway, it's something you might
try as you listen to the sound

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:23.960
from the Grampians dawn chorus.

00:36:23.960 --> 00:37:23.130
[ Bird Sounds ]

00:37:23.130 --> 00:37:30.970
There is a layer of complexity,
a layer of complexity

00:37:30.970 --> 00:37:37.690
of the bird sounds, that mostly
we don't hear unless we slow the

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:39.380
sound down.

00:37:39.380 --> 00:37:42.290
So, it [inaudible] heard in
the springtime and the fall

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:45.910
and these are recordings now of
birds in the wood thrush family,

00:37:45.910 --> 00:37:51.990
the wood thrush, hermit
thrush veery at normal speeds

00:37:51.990 --> 00:37:59.190
and then slowed down and you'll
hear what the recording reveal.

00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:06.090
[ Bird Sounds ]

00:38:06.090 --> 00:38:08.510
That's normal speed.

00:38:08.510 --> 00:38:52.040
[ Bird Sounds ]

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:55.200
Isn't that wonderful?

00:38:55.200 --> 00:39:01.350
Birds, of course, can
also talk or mimic.

00:39:01.350 --> 00:39:07.010
This is another serendipitous
moment and it's a conversation

00:39:07.010 --> 00:39:12.130
between a girl and talking
parrot that we, it was recorded

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:15.450
in Brazil so they're
speaking Portuguese

00:39:15.450 --> 00:39:19.450
and you'll hear the parrot
on one side I forget which

00:39:19.450 --> 00:39:26.010
and the girl on the other,
I'll point them out to you.

00:39:26.010 --> 00:39:27.370
[ Bird Sounds ]

00:39:27.370 --> 00:39:28.670
That's the girl.

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:33.510
That's the parrot.

00:39:33.510 --> 00:40:04.270
[ Bird Sounds ]

00:40:04.270 --> 00:40:06.460
So, what she's saying
is "I'm mad at you."

00:40:06.460 --> 00:40:08.160
And guy says "I'm mad at you."

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:11.330
She say, "You're mad at me?

00:40:11.330 --> 00:40:13.270
I'm mad at you."

00:40:13.270 --> 00:40:16.500
This may be as closest to object
art as you'll hear tonight

00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:20.110
because every, in the sense
that every, I've listened

00:40:20.110 --> 00:40:22.660
to that recording
countless times

00:40:22.660 --> 00:40:26.100
and every time I hear it it
just brings a smile to my face,

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:29.360
so it's one of these things.

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:31.840
So, you've made a
memorable recording.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:36.620
You've been given this gift,
this little nugget of audio gold

00:40:36.620 --> 00:40:38.380
and now you're dying
to share it,

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:42.680
because this active sharing
is imperative that we have

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:46.080
in common with virtually every
other living thing on earth,

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:49.500
this need to connect
and to commune.

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:52.020
In this case, to share
what you tuned into,

00:40:52.020 --> 00:40:54.740
this thing that touched
you deeply.

00:40:54.740 --> 00:40:59.200
So, now you search for a context
that you can grab somebody

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:00.500
by the ears and say, "Hey,

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:03.220
listen to this", so
what would it be?"

00:41:03.220 --> 00:41:05.250
Is it going to be a CD?

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:06.550
Well, it may be.

00:41:06.550 --> 00:41:11.910
In fact, I have two CDs right
here that you're welcome to buy

00:41:11.910 --> 00:41:13.600
if you want to later on.

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:18.090
I only got two of some of
the sounds you've heard,

00:41:18.090 --> 00:41:23.390
but what I have done
mostly is not sell CDs,

00:41:23.390 --> 00:41:27.320
it's to make radio
programs and now podcasts.

00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:33.280
And you make it and you
cross your finger or fingers

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:35.750
as the case may be, and you hope

00:41:35.750 --> 00:41:38.240
that somebody will
actually pay attention.

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:46.590
Well, one approach is to
frame a sound in a story.

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:49.100
So, here's an early Pulse
of the Planet program

00:41:49.100 --> 00:41:52.910
which demonstrates that
possibility of framing a sound

00:41:52.910 --> 00:41:55.430
within a little story.

00:41:55.430 --> 00:42:00.570
A group of pilot whales that
beach themselves and now

00:42:00.570 --> 00:42:02.660
as the tide was falling,
word was getting

00:42:02.660 --> 00:42:07.760
out at Cape Cod's [inaudible] of
volunteers was coming to rescue.

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:10.750
I'm Jim Metzner and this
is the Pulse of the Planet.

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:14.220
&gt;&gt; Right now the tide is going
out and these animals are going

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:16.640
to be high and dry for
the foreseeable future

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:19.020
that is either until
the next tide comes

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:20.730
up to float them
12 hours from now

00:42:20.730 --> 00:42:22.660
or until we can pick
them up and move them.

00:42:22.660 --> 00:42:24.790
We're checking out the area
right now looking for pools

00:42:24.790 --> 00:42:27.360
that remain after the tide
goes out and we may be able

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:29.260
to move them and keep
them in those pools,

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:31.470
that would be the best scenario.

00:42:31.470 --> 00:42:32.770
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Dave Wyman is

00:42:32.770 --> 00:42:34.680
with the International
Wildlife Coalition,

00:42:34.680 --> 00:42:36.250
one of the many environmental
groups

00:42:36.250 --> 00:42:38.920
that come together
during a whale rescue.

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:41.810
&gt;&gt; Right now we're covering
them with blankets and sheets,

00:42:41.810 --> 00:42:43.990
one to keep the sun off
them and keep them moist,

00:42:43.990 --> 00:42:47.320
and also in some degree
to help them control their

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:48.620
body temperature.

00:42:48.620 --> 00:42:50.830
They can quickly overheat
in a situation like this,

00:42:50.830 --> 00:42:55.750
so we'll keep the water
on them to keep them cool

00:42:55.750 --> 00:42:59.920
or in some cases if they go

00:42:59.920 --> 00:43:03.300
into shock they can
start getting cold.

00:43:03.300 --> 00:43:09.900
In that case, we'll use other
things and put more blankets

00:43:09.900 --> 00:43:14.050
on them and try to
keep them warm.

00:43:14.050 --> 00:43:19.500
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Why
expand all this effort

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:21.050
for these stranded whales?

00:43:21.050 --> 00:43:28.770
Why not let nature
take its course?

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:31.530
&gt;&gt; Well, we don't know
what nature's course is

00:43:31.530 --> 00:43:34.180
and so it's very
difficult to stand back

00:43:34.180 --> 00:43:37.170
and just say well
this is nature's way.

00:43:37.170 --> 00:43:41.370
It's like when people in India
they say well somebody's karma

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:44.590
to drown, well maybe it's
you time to save them

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:48.910
and that's kind of a roundabout
answer, but right we're doing

00:43:48.910 --> 00:43:50.670
so many negative things to
the planet that it's nice

00:43:50.670 --> 00:43:51.970
to have one thing
that you can do

00:43:51.970 --> 00:43:53.270
that has maybe a
positive influence

00:43:53.270 --> 00:43:54.570
and this certainly does.

00:43:54.570 --> 00:43:55.870
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: It's true.

00:43:55.870 --> 00:43:57.170
After a while I put down my
microphones and lend a hand

00:43:57.170 --> 00:43:58.470
in the rescue operation.

00:43:58.470 --> 00:43:59.770
Looking into the eye of a whale
close up and hearing it breathe

00:43:59.770 --> 00:44:01.070
and vocalize was the
only payment that any

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:02.370
of us volunteers expected,
that and the feeling

00:44:02.370 --> 00:44:03.670
that maybe just maybe I'll save
the life of a fellow creature.

00:44:03.670 --> 00:44:04.970
This archival program is part

00:44:04.970 --> 00:44:06.270
of our 30th anniversary
celebration.

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:07.570
If you want to hear more,
checkout our podcast.

00:44:07.570 --> 00:44:08.870
So, sound can also reveal
something unexpected even

00:44:08.870 --> 00:44:11.170
in a familiar territory.

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:16.940
&gt;&gt; And you got really make the
point and believe in the strike.

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:23.880
So, however you go about that
that's your own personal style

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:25.180
[crowd cheering].

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:26.480
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: What separates
one major league umpire

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:27.780
from another?

00:44:27.780 --> 00:44:30.170
It's a personal style
based primarily on sound.

00:44:30.170 --> 00:44:33.170
We talked with three American
League umps in Seattle recently

00:44:33.170 --> 00:44:34.790
and they demonstrated and talked

00:44:34.790 --> 00:44:37.290
about why they sound
the way they do.

00:44:37.290 --> 00:44:40.570
I'm Jim Metzner and you're
hearing America recorded

00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:41.870
on Maxell tape.

00:44:41.870 --> 00:44:44.260
&gt;&gt; Well, I've never said
strike in my career.

00:44:44.260 --> 00:44:46.240
I just never could
get out steeeri,

00:44:46.240 --> 00:44:47.750
I just couldn't get it out.

00:44:47.750 --> 00:44:50.450
Yeah, that's a strike.

00:44:50.450 --> 00:44:54.200
But you really got to feel it.

00:44:54.200 --> 00:44:56.000
Yeah! That's it.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.780
[ Crowd Cheering ]

00:44:58.780 --> 00:45:03.230
&gt;&gt; Mine is a one
that I just go A!

00:45:03.230 --> 00:45:04.530
like that.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:07.530
And the strike three
is I'll reach in

00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:09.140
and pull back and it's A-A!

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:10.440
like that.

00:45:10.440 --> 00:45:14.150
It looks like a karate
move, but you know, it works

00:45:14.150 --> 00:45:18.080
and then a lot of times the
louder you are you're drowning

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:21.070
out a lot of the criticism
too, so by the time I'm done

00:45:21.070 --> 00:45:25.240
with my opera, you know,
they're not yelling too much.

00:45:25.240 --> 00:45:31.290
&gt;&gt; And my particular
deal is just Ya!

00:45:31.290 --> 00:45:34.750
Three! Would be strike three.

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:36.050
&gt;&gt; Free?

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:37.350
&gt;&gt; Three. Free!

00:45:37.350 --> 00:45:38.650
&gt;&gt; And we call them from
our heart, you know,

00:45:38.650 --> 00:45:41.990
basically we don't care who wins
the ballgame, so the idea is

00:45:41.990 --> 00:45:44.830
to go out there and try and get
in as little trouble as possible

00:45:44.830 --> 00:45:47.100
and if you're aggressive out
there and you sell yourself,

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:49.360
you know, a lot of
times you'll stay

00:45:49.360 --> 00:45:51.520
out of arguments by
being aggressive.

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:55.980
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: My thanks
to American League umpires,

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:59.220
Larry Barnett, Durwood
Merrill, and Rocky Roe.

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:02.250
I'm Jim Metzner and you're
hearing American recorded

00:46:02.250 --> 00:46:03.710
on Maxell tape.

00:46:03.710 --> 00:46:06.510
Maxell, it's worth it.

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:12.510
[ Crowd Cheering ]

00:46:12.510 --> 00:46:15.890
That was one of the predecessors
of Pulse of the Planet,

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:20.310
one of the series that I
think Matt had mentioned.

00:46:20.310 --> 00:46:26.770
Well, my favorite is I-E.

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:29.580
Sometimes you'll
be out recording

00:46:29.580 --> 00:46:33.680
and there's certain sounds,
certain places where you feel

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:36.720
like you're being
kind of pulled along.

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:38.210
The sounds are pulling you.

00:46:38.210 --> 00:46:40.350
You're taking this journey.

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:44.240
So, we're going to now take
a little journey in sound

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:49.230
and this journey is to Morocco,

00:46:49.230 --> 00:46:52.590
one of the great
cities of Morocco.

00:46:52.590 --> 00:46:58.540
A tape recorder is a
pocketful of breadcrumbs.

00:46:58.540 --> 00:47:01.350
When you record sounds
wherever you go,

00:47:01.350 --> 00:47:04.840
you leave an invisible
trail from moment to moment

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:07.670
and then one day, you
listen to the tape

00:47:07.670 --> 00:47:10.510
and you find your
way back again.

00:47:10.510 --> 00:47:13.060
[ Background Conversations ]

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:16.180
This trail leads to
Morocco, the city of Fes.

00:47:16.180 --> 00:47:19.610
One of the oldest continuously
inhabited cities in the world.

00:47:19.610 --> 00:47:24.510
Let's follow these sounds
and see where they take us.

00:47:24.510 --> 00:47:28.560
[ Background Conversations ]

00:47:28.560 --> 00:47:30.720
Fes is really three cities;

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:34.160
the first a modern
European style metropolis;

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:37.780
the second Fes El-Jadid
or "new Fes" dates

00:47:37.780 --> 00:47:43.190
from the 13th century; and
"old Fes" Fes El-Bali goes back

00:47:43.190 --> 00:47:47.880
to the 9th century and
that's where we are now.

00:47:47.880 --> 00:47:52.750
Picture an ancient walled city
and inside the walls is a maze

00:47:52.750 --> 00:47:56.190
of alleyways too narrow
for a car to get through,

00:47:56.190 --> 00:48:02.510
so the traffic inside old Fes
is mostly people and donkeys.

00:48:02.510 --> 00:48:13.110
[ Background Conversations ]

00:48:13.110 --> 00:48:15.330
Balick [phonetic] is the
donkey driver's equivalent

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:20.010
of a car horn and it
means, out of the way.

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:21.310
[ Background Conversation ]

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:24.880
Two hundred twenty-five thousand
people inhabit the old city

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:29.010
of Fes in an area roughly
four-and-a-half square miles.

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:30.490
For the folks who live here,

00:48:30.490 --> 00:48:33.510
it's one enormous
extended family.

00:48:33.510 --> 00:48:37.600
For a child growing up here, the
alleyways of the old city are

00:48:37.600 --> 00:48:44.270
on extended playground
[children playing].

00:48:44.270 --> 00:48:48.360
Amidst the bustle of activity
in the city always in motion

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:51.680
like a giant human
hive and the moments

00:48:51.680 --> 00:48:58.180
when the sounds themselves
will slow you right down.

00:48:58.180 --> 00:49:01.560
In a tunnel passageway with
children playing nearby

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.450
and tourists and trades
people walking past,

00:49:04.450 --> 00:49:09.510
an old man intones
praises to Iman.

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:20.450
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:24.390
Morocco is an Islamic
country and in Fes' Medina,

00:49:24.390 --> 00:49:26.380
that's another name
for the "old city",

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:29.080
there are literally
hundreds of mosques.

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:31.680
Five times a day you
can hear the call

00:49:31.680 --> 00:49:34.940
to prayer throughout the city,
but probably the best place

00:49:34.940 --> 00:49:36.950
to hear it is from a rooftop

00:49:36.950 --> 00:49:40.510
when it's just you
and the pigeons.

00:49:40.510 --> 00:50:42.120
[ Background Sounds ]

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:45.090
Non-Muslims are not
allowed inside mosques,

00:50:45.090 --> 00:50:49.030
but it is possible to gain
entrance to a koranic school,

00:50:49.030 --> 00:50:52.460
men who live and work in this
part of the Medina come here

00:50:52.460 --> 00:50:56.290
to pray, but before they
do, they remove their shoes

00:50:56.290 --> 00:51:00.050
and wash their feet, hands
and face at the fountain

00:51:00.050 --> 00:51:02.510
in the school's courtyard.

00:51:02.510 --> 00:51:19.600
[ Water Sounds/Bird Sounds ]

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:22.330
As a flock of birds
circles overhead,

00:51:22.330 --> 00:51:26.510
the Iman begins is prayer
facing towards Mecca and a row

00:51:26.510 --> 00:51:31.510
of a dozen men standing
shoulder to shoulder join in.

00:51:31.510 --> 00:52:08.050
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:52:08.050 --> 00:52:11.450
Outside the courtyard
of the koranic school,

00:52:11.450 --> 00:52:14.660
the life of the Medina hums
right along and it's easy

00:52:14.660 --> 00:52:17.350
to be drawn through the
alleyways and tunnels

00:52:17.350 --> 00:52:20.510
from one sound to another.

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:30.240
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:52:30.240 --> 00:52:32.460
[ Bell Ringing ]

00:52:32.460 --> 00:52:35.300
That's the [foreign word spoken]
who carries a goatskin full

00:52:35.300 --> 00:52:38.070
of water and dispenses
it in a brass cup

00:52:38.070 --> 00:52:40.770
to anyone who requires a drink.

00:52:40.770 --> 00:52:43.840
Along with the bell,
his signature sound,

00:52:43.840 --> 00:52:46.450
they [foreign word spoken]
wears a broad-rim hat fringed

00:52:46.450 --> 00:52:50.640
with tassels and a costume
bedecked with tiny mirrors

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:54.260
and for a few dirham,
the Moroccan currency,

00:52:54.260 --> 00:52:56.510
he'll let you take his picture.

00:52:56.510 --> 00:53:02.050
[ Background Conversations/Bell
Ringing ]

00:53:02.050 --> 00:53:05.480
The passageways of the old
city are lined with stores

00:53:05.480 --> 00:53:07.750
and stalls selling
a mix of modern

00:53:07.750 --> 00:53:11.540
and more traditional goods;
foods of every description,

00:53:11.540 --> 00:53:16.080
but most especially dates
and olives, spices, clothing,

00:53:16.080 --> 00:53:20.360
hardware, dry goods, school
supplies, electrical supplies,

00:53:20.360 --> 00:53:22.840
video games, and cassettes.

00:53:22.840 --> 00:53:26.060
There are boom boxes
everywhere here and they compete

00:53:26.060 --> 00:53:29.510
for a niche in the
rock sound scheme.

00:53:29.510 --> 00:53:40.510
[ Music ]

00:53:40.510 --> 00:53:50.580
[ Background Conversations ]

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:53.100
In the ecology of
the marketplace,

00:53:53.100 --> 00:53:57.490
tourists are both predator
and prey, taking photographs

00:53:57.490 --> 00:54:00.950
at every opportunity of the
people who, for the most part,

00:54:00.950 --> 00:54:03.440
really don't want to
have their picture taken.

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:07.150
In turn, the busloads of
turistas who make their rounds

00:54:07.150 --> 00:54:10.400
through the Medina
are hit on by hawkers,

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:13.630
stall keepers and
would-be guides.

00:54:13.630 --> 00:54:16.780
The sounds of bargaining
ripple through the Medina

00:54:16.780 --> 00:54:21.510
and the merchants of Fes
are masters salesmen.

00:54:21.510 --> 00:54:27.240
[ Background Conversations ]

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:29.040
&gt;&gt; This is all [background
conversations].

00:54:29.040 --> 00:54:35.410
Bronze all, all bronze,
50 dirhams.

00:54:35.410 --> 00:54:39.850
&gt;&gt; It's not the deal that is
important, it is your friendship

00:54:39.850 --> 00:54:41.330
for next time perhaps.

00:54:41.330 --> 00:54:48.510
So, money is not of 600 dirham
you won't regret [inaudible].

00:54:48.510 --> 00:54:51.050
[ Background Conversations ]

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:54.200
There are settler sonic
delights in the old city,

00:54:54.200 --> 00:54:56.990
somewhat off the beaten
pathways like the sound

00:54:56.990 --> 00:55:01.510
of grain being sifted before
it's grounded to flour.

00:55:01.510 --> 00:55:05.690
[ Background Sounds ]

00:55:05.690 --> 00:55:08.290
Or the noise made by a
little hand motor used

00:55:08.290 --> 00:55:11.390
to twist the cotton thread
for making djellabas,

00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:13.200
the traditional men's
outer garment.

00:55:13.200 --> 00:55:23.120
Fes has a rich tradition
of craftsmenship.

00:55:23.120 --> 00:55:26.620
Whole sections of the old city
belong to artists who work

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:31.840
in brass, stone,
textiles, wood and leather.

00:55:31.840 --> 00:55:36.800
In the [foreign word spoken] the
stone chiselers work nearby the

00:55:36.800 --> 00:55:40.380
men who hammer the
designs on brass trays

00:55:40.380 --> 00:55:43.050
and sometimes it seems
as though the rhythm

00:55:43.050 --> 00:55:46.510
of one is picked up by another.

00:55:46.510 --> 00:56:09.450
[ Hammering Sounds/Background
Conversations ]

00:56:09.450 --> 00:56:14.200
And then suddenly it's dusk
and the trail of sound morsels,

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:18.000
expands and intersperses
throughout the old city.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:21.230
There is magic in the air and
what better place to hear it

00:56:21.230 --> 00:56:24.120
than at the Bab Boujeloud,
the Blue Gate,

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:27.790
the place where most people
enter and leave the Medina.

00:56:27.790 --> 00:56:31.480
In the throngs of humanity
that parade by, and in those

00:56:31.480 --> 00:56:33.540
that the cafés that
sit and watch them.

00:56:33.540 --> 00:56:37.430
There's an air of
expectancy echoed by the birds

00:56:37.430 --> 00:56:39.420
who roost here as
if in the midst

00:56:39.420 --> 00:56:43.200
of all this apparent chaos
there's a last minute chance

00:56:43.200 --> 00:56:47.920
to make some sense of it all,
and for a fleeting moment,

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:52.510
the music that is hidden
in all sounds reappears.

00:56:52.510 --> 00:57:14.510
[ Background Conversations/Bird
Sounds ]

00:57:14.510 --> 00:57:42.510
[ Background Conversations/Bird
Sounds/Music ]

00:57:42.510 --> 00:58:25.390
[ Music ]

00:58:25.390 --> 00:58:30.330
From Fes in Morocco, I'm
Jim Metzner the savvy

00:58:30.330 --> 00:58:33.040
traveler [music].

00:58:33.040 --> 00:58:37.160
That really together
continues just a little further

00:58:37.160 --> 00:58:43.890
with the idea that songs and
stories are among the gifts

00:58:43.890 --> 00:58:47.490
that we've been given as
guides to help us navigate

00:58:47.490 --> 00:58:50.600
through our collective journeys.

00:58:50.600 --> 00:58:55.450
Some Native American
tribes have song carriers,

00:58:55.450 --> 00:58:59.020
people who have been entrusted
with specific songs to keep

00:58:59.020 --> 00:59:02.550
through over the generations.

00:59:02.550 --> 00:59:08.990
Storytellers carry the tales of
our ancestors and of our times

00:59:08.990 --> 00:59:15.510
and a great storyteller
invokes a very special quality

00:59:15.510 --> 00:59:16.810
of listening.

00:59:16.810 --> 00:59:22.330
&gt;&gt; I could go forever
without repeating a story,

00:59:22.330 --> 00:59:23.690
stories from all over,

00:59:23.690 --> 00:59:27.460
I am a storytelling
cat that's what I am.

00:59:27.460 --> 00:59:30.620
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: You're
hearing Boston on WEIFM.

00:59:30.620 --> 00:59:34.550
In the next two minutes
we'll talk with Brother Blue.

00:59:34.550 --> 00:59:36.150
&gt;&gt; I'm only known
as Brother Blue.

00:59:36.150 --> 00:59:39.150
Nobody calls me anything but
Brother Blue except my mama.

00:59:39.150 --> 00:59:40.450
You know how mama's are?

00:59:40.450 --> 00:59:44.070
"I named you Hugh", okay ma.

00:59:44.070 --> 00:59:46.300
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: On a sunny
day on a traffic island

00:59:46.300 --> 00:59:49.680
in the middle of Harvard Square,
there's a man all dressed

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:54.790
in blue with barrels and ribbons
and butterflies all over him.

00:59:54.790 --> 00:59:57.720
Brother Blue begins
telling stories to anyone

00:59:57.720 --> 00:59:59.480
who will stop and listen.

00:59:59.480 --> 01:00:01.240
Already a crowd has gathered

01:00:01.240 --> 01:00:05.510
and magically someone
begins to sing.

01:00:05.510 --> 01:00:37.140
[ Singing ]

01:00:37.140 --> 01:00:41.690
&gt;&gt; Daddy comes in the door while
mama's singing Amazing Grace

01:00:41.690 --> 01:00:43.350
for Blue you know.

01:00:43.350 --> 01:00:44.650
It's cold on me.

01:00:44.650 --> 01:00:48.210
When I got out in the little
square, Harvard Square,

01:00:48.210 --> 01:00:51.670
that is my blue [inaudible]
where all the beautiful things

01:00:51.670 --> 01:00:54.600
and when my lions come
out and my dragons.

01:00:54.600 --> 01:00:58.520
And all you have to do is
cross the sea of traffic.

01:00:58.520 --> 01:01:02.900
I don't care if they are sirens
blowing, there's firemen going

01:01:02.900 --> 01:01:07.900
by and police whistles, on that
island we get into that blue,

01:01:07.900 --> 01:01:09.980
blue country which
is imagination.

01:01:09.980 --> 01:01:13.070
Give me your feet.

01:01:13.070 --> 01:01:15.990
He's rubbing my feet while
mama sings [singing].

01:01:15.990 --> 01:01:21.050
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: The next
time you're in Harvard Square

01:01:21.050 --> 01:01:23.360
and you want to hear
a great storyteller,

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:26.910
just keep a lookout
for that Blue island.

01:01:26.910 --> 01:01:33.420
I'm Jim Metzner, and you're
hearing Boston on WEIFM-103.

01:01:33.420 --> 01:01:39.850
&gt;&gt; It's possible to tell a
story to transform the listener

01:01:39.850 --> 01:01:41.940
and the teller of the story

01:01:41.940 --> 01:01:44.330
and I believe they can
transform the world.

01:01:44.330 --> 01:01:48.300
When I ask you I want
you to all sing with me.

01:01:48.300 --> 01:01:51.660
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: So, perhaps
inspired by the fact that we are

01:01:51.660 --> 01:01:58.180
in one of the greatest libraries
of the world here, I'm wondering

01:01:58.180 --> 01:02:01.800
if we could say that
song carriers

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:08.460
and storytellers are both
organic sound architects.

01:02:08.460 --> 01:02:10.800
What do you think Matt?

01:02:10.800 --> 01:02:15.020
Make a case for that maybe?

01:02:15.020 --> 01:02:16.320
&gt;&gt; Mathew Barton: Yeah.

01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:17.620
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yes.

01:02:17.620 --> 01:02:21.980
Taking it one step further,
what if each of us in his

01:02:21.980 --> 01:02:26.610
or her own way is
a sound carrier?

01:02:26.610 --> 01:02:29.530
A sound carrier.

01:02:29.530 --> 01:02:33.430
What if we carry those
vibrations within us

01:02:33.430 --> 01:02:36.540
that have left a
deep impression?

01:02:36.540 --> 01:02:40.500
What if inside each of
us there is a repository,

01:02:40.500 --> 01:02:44.450
a unique library of memorable
sounds that we've heard

01:02:44.450 --> 01:02:49.990
in our lifetime which return
on occasion accompanied usually

01:02:49.990 --> 01:02:52.360
by waves of nostalgia?

01:02:52.360 --> 01:02:57.930
Well, I spent a year doing
interviews collecting sound

01:02:57.930 --> 01:03:03.000
memories asking people this
question which is sort of like

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:05.600
when you got the response
and I got it a lot it was

01:03:05.600 --> 01:03:07.610
like striking emotional oil.

01:03:07.610 --> 01:03:10.120
What sound kind of entered
into you and never left,

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:13.520
the sound you could hear
even now in your bones?

01:03:13.520 --> 01:03:16.200
And then the challenge
in creating this story

01:03:16.200 --> 01:03:20.820
that framed it, was to
either recreate or collect

01:03:20.820 --> 01:03:22.120
or recreate those sounds.

01:03:22.120 --> 01:03:26.030
So, this is just an excerpt
from Sound Memories which ran

01:03:26.030 --> 01:03:30.510
on all things considered
some years back.

01:03:30.510 --> 01:03:37.040
[ Frying Sounds ]

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:42.280
&gt;&gt; Sunday morning, I would be
up in my bedroom early and down

01:03:42.280 --> 01:03:46.850
in the kitchen my mother
would be making tomato sauce

01:03:46.850 --> 01:03:49.840
and as the oil would
heat up with the garlic,

01:03:49.840 --> 01:03:52.480
she would pour the
tomatoes in and as soon

01:03:52.480 --> 01:03:56.070
as the tomatoes hit there would
be a sizzle and I would hear

01:03:56.070 --> 01:03:58.490
that sound and the
entire house would explode

01:03:58.490 --> 01:04:04.150
with this wonderful aroma and
the scent, and it never left me

01:04:04.150 --> 01:04:08.510
and I could almost
taste it as I hear it.

01:04:08.510 --> 01:04:13.070
[ Frying Sounds ]

01:04:13.070 --> 01:04:24.880
&gt;&gt; I can still hear my
father in the kitchen singing

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:26.760
and he would just stroll up
and down the hall in the house

01:04:26.760 --> 01:04:28.060
when I was growing
up with his hands

01:04:28.060 --> 01:04:29.400
in his pockets I could hear the
change jingling in his pockets

01:04:29.400 --> 01:04:30.700
because he worked for Manhattan

01:04:30.700 --> 01:04:32.000
that it needs all the
coins in those days.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:33.300
You needed coins
for subway tokens

01:04:33.300 --> 01:04:35.100
and he would be saying,
"Do-do-do."

01:04:35.100 --> 01:04:56.340
[ Singing/Music ]

01:04:56.340 --> 01:04:58.050
&gt;&gt; My mother was Scottish
and every Sunday morning

01:04:58.050 --> 01:05:00.660
at 8 AM she would put the
pipes and drums on full volume

01:05:00.660 --> 01:05:02.830
and I woke up to that every
Sunday morning of my life

01:05:02.830 --> 01:05:06.510
and that made a very
deep impression on me.

01:05:06.510 --> 01:05:22.520
[ Pipe Music ]

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:24.940
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: It was sounds
that got you out of the house.

01:05:24.940 --> 01:05:27.830
Maybe they drove you
out, maybe they drew you.

01:05:27.830 --> 01:05:29.760
Now I'm listening back

01:05:29.760 --> 01:05:34.790
and inviting you again the fire
alarm, the ice cream truck,

01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:37.420
the card that your friend
attached with the clothespin

01:05:37.420 --> 01:05:40.690
to the fender of his bicycle
made it sound like a motorcycle.

01:05:40.690 --> 01:05:44.680
Or the first time you ever
went somewhere just to listen

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:50.510
to the sounds there it was
underneath the Brooklyn Bridge.

01:05:50.510 --> 01:06:15.530
[ Background Sounds ]

01:06:15.530 --> 01:06:18.330
Sounds do have a
life of their own.

01:06:18.330 --> 01:06:20.930
They can take you to
undiscovered places,

01:06:20.930 --> 01:06:25.100
but more often than not, they'll
take you back to the brink

01:06:25.100 --> 01:06:31.920
of memory to a moment that
was catalyzed by sound.

01:06:31.920 --> 01:06:35.160
&gt;&gt; When I was really young,
I had a favorite uncle

01:06:35.160 --> 01:06:37.060
who lived with us for a while.

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:41.450
He used to tell me stories
and we had this habit,

01:06:41.450 --> 01:06:45.080
he would stretch out on the
floor and with a big bowel

01:06:45.080 --> 01:06:48.440
of apples next to him and tell
me stories while I rested my

01:06:48.440 --> 01:06:49.900
head on his stomach.

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:53.170
All of these stories
were accentuated by the.

01:06:53.170 --> 01:06:54.470
&gt;&gt; Let's lie down.

01:06:54.470 --> 01:06:58.060
&gt;&gt; Of the apple and so
the sound of his breathing

01:06:58.060 --> 01:07:00.520
and whenever I hear the sound
of an apple being bitten

01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:02.760
into there's a little
bit of the.

01:07:02.760 --> 01:07:04.060
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Once
upon a time.

01:07:04.060 --> 01:07:05.770
&gt;&gt; Pleasantness that
was connected

01:07:05.770 --> 01:07:07.480
with those experiences.

01:07:07.480 --> 01:07:08.780
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: There
was princess

01:07:08.780 --> 01:07:10.850
who lived in a big castle.

01:07:10.850 --> 01:07:14.420
Want a bite?

01:07:14.420 --> 01:07:15.720
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:07:15.720 --> 01:07:19.640
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: In far,
far away in a forest,

01:07:19.640 --> 01:07:25.690
there lived a very mean ogre.

01:07:25.690 --> 01:07:30.120
You know how many heads he had?

01:07:30.120 --> 01:07:31.480
&gt;&gt; How many?

01:07:31.480 --> 01:07:32.780
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Five.

01:07:32.780 --> 01:07:34.080
Five.

01:07:34.080 --> 01:07:37.190
&gt;&gt; One, 2, 3, 4, 5.

01:07:37.190 --> 01:07:38.490
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yeah.

01:07:38.490 --> 01:07:39.790
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

01:07:39.790 --> 01:07:43.360
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: And this ogre
used to eat little children

01:07:43.360 --> 01:07:48.350
that would come by and.

01:07:48.350 --> 01:07:49.650
&gt;&gt; Stop.

01:07:49.650 --> 01:07:50.950
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: [Inaudible]

01:07:50.950 --> 01:07:52.250
&gt;&gt; Stop.

01:07:52.250 --> 01:07:53.550
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: [Inaudible].

01:07:53.550 --> 01:07:54.850
&gt;&gt; Stop, stop.

01:07:54.850 --> 01:07:56.150
&gt;&gt; Just several years
ago on the West Coast

01:07:56.150 --> 01:07:57.520
of British Columbia I
found an abandoned seal pup

01:07:57.520 --> 01:08:01.660
and spent the night with
it sleeping on my stomach

01:08:01.660 --> 01:08:07.070
and its cries awakened something
incredibly maternal within me

01:08:07.070 --> 01:08:11.730
to which I wasn't aware of and I
still hear those haunting cries

01:08:11.730 --> 01:08:15.510
that really settled into
the core of my being.

01:08:15.510 --> 01:08:22.310
[ Background Sounds ]

01:08:22.310 --> 01:08:27.710
&gt;&gt; Growing up in Algiers
during the war in 1959 to 62,

01:08:27.710 --> 01:08:31.890
we lived in Hydra in the
southern part of the city

01:08:31.890 --> 01:08:35.390
and periodically there
would be bombings

01:08:35.390 --> 01:08:37.090
and those would happen
mostly at night,

01:08:37.090 --> 01:08:40.360
and so one of the most
powerful sound memories

01:08:40.360 --> 01:08:44.220
that I have was the
low percussive thud

01:08:44.220 --> 01:08:47.650
of bombs going off
around the city

01:08:47.650 --> 01:08:52.650
and the way the vibrations
would transfer into the walls

01:08:52.650 --> 01:08:56.940
of the house and the metal
shutters by my bedroom window.

01:08:56.940 --> 01:09:01.740
Often concurrent with
that on these evenings

01:09:01.740 --> 01:09:05.970
with warm breezes coming up
from the valley to the south

01:09:05.970 --> 01:09:10.320
of the city, would carry
slightly modulated voices

01:09:10.320 --> 01:09:14.460
of Berber tribeswomen
ululating and that would sort

01:09:14.460 --> 01:09:17.910
of envelop the house and the
sound that was once beautiful,

01:09:17.910 --> 01:09:21.510
but also terrifying
on some levels.

01:09:21.510 --> 01:09:40.040
[ Bomb Sounds ]

01:09:40.040 --> 01:09:47.830
&gt;&gt; Long ago it was in 58-59 we
went all outside into the van,

01:09:47.830 --> 01:09:54.390
it was late maybe midnight
and suddenly looking

01:09:54.390 --> 01:09:58.350
to just [background
conversations] we saw light

01:09:58.350 --> 01:10:01.240
in the sky and it was coming.

01:10:01.240 --> 01:10:06.140
&gt;&gt; When I first heard the
sound I thought it was maybe a

01:10:06.140 --> 01:10:10.340
low-flying jet and then I
thought well maybe it's a couple

01:10:10.340 --> 01:10:13.600
of low-flying jets and then
it sounded really like a fleet

01:10:13.600 --> 01:10:15.950
of low-flying jets
and then, you know,

01:10:15.950 --> 01:10:17.660
we ran outside to
see this light.

01:10:17.660 --> 01:10:23.040
&gt;&gt; Light in the sky and it
was coming from left to right,

01:10:23.040 --> 01:10:25.720
but the most [inaudible]
was the sound.

01:10:25.720 --> 01:10:27.020
&gt;&gt; Sound.

01:10:27.020 --> 01:10:31.140
&gt;&gt; It was like something
in the wind, something.

01:10:31.140 --> 01:10:32.440
&gt;&gt; Loud.

01:10:32.440 --> 01:10:36.030
&gt;&gt; Between the wind
and something metallic.

01:10:36.030 --> 01:10:39.840
&gt;&gt; That I felt that if it
were any louder at all,

01:10:39.840 --> 01:10:42.970
that everything me and all life

01:10:42.970 --> 01:10:45.070
around me would have
been shattered.

01:10:45.070 --> 01:10:46.560
&gt;&gt; Something I will
never forget.

01:10:46.560 --> 01:10:48.510
Never.

01:10:48.510 --> 01:11:06.510
[ Jet Plane Sounds ]

01:11:06.510 --> 01:11:17.600
[ Rain/Hail ]

01:11:17.600 --> 01:11:22.180
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: So,
we're all sound carriers.

01:11:22.180 --> 01:11:29.530
Hopefully this has raised
collective antennae a bit

01:11:29.530 --> 01:11:37.370
and I'm wondering if there
are any questions or sounds

01:11:37.370 --> 01:11:43.170
or sound memories that you have
that you want to share with us?

01:11:43.170 --> 01:11:46.140
Anybody have a sound memory?

01:11:46.140 --> 01:11:49.530
Something that stayed
with you that came back

01:11:49.530 --> 01:11:52.750
as you were thinking of this?

01:11:52.750 --> 01:11:56.400
Don't be shy.

01:11:56.400 --> 01:11:58.200
Yeah. Nancy.

01:11:58.200 --> 01:12:02.630
&gt;&gt; I climbed the Virungas to
see the gorillas over in Rwanda.

01:12:02.630 --> 01:12:08.160
We went up through these
carved farmlands and we went

01:12:08.160 --> 01:12:11.900
up the mountain and the line
of demarcation between that

01:12:11.900 --> 01:12:15.300
and then this really incredible
journey that we were going

01:12:15.300 --> 01:12:19.360
to be taking that day, was
stepping into a bamboo forest.

01:12:19.360 --> 01:12:24.090
It was the first time I had
been in one [inaudible] since,

01:12:24.090 --> 01:12:27.330
but I never forgot this because
it was literally like going

01:12:27.330 --> 01:12:30.570
through a curtain to
another place and all

01:12:30.570 --> 01:12:34.050
of a sudden the sounds were
completely different and part

01:12:34.050 --> 01:12:39.340
of it was the, the birds and
the whatever other critters were

01:12:39.340 --> 01:12:41.220
living up high in the canopy

01:12:41.220 --> 01:12:44.260
of this forest were
complete different

01:12:44.260 --> 01:12:48.030
than they had been two steps
over outside of it, and also,

01:12:48.030 --> 01:12:50.140
I think the thing I most
remember is the sound

01:12:50.140 --> 01:12:53.330
of the bamboo, the sound of
crossing it and clattering

01:12:53.330 --> 01:12:57.880
and clicking in this really
musical pattern way high

01:12:57.880 --> 01:12:59.390
up above us.

01:12:59.390 --> 01:13:00.690
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: That's great.

01:13:00.690 --> 01:13:01.990
That's a great sound
and I've heard,

01:13:01.990 --> 01:13:04.630
I've never heard this myself,
but I've heard and told me

01:13:04.630 --> 01:13:07.410
that in certain conditions
you can actually hear

01:13:07.410 --> 01:13:08.710
bamboo growing.

01:13:08.710 --> 01:13:11.180
I don't know if that's
true or not.

01:13:11.180 --> 01:13:13.720
But wow, what an amazing sound.

01:13:13.720 --> 01:13:15.020
Thank you.

01:13:15.020 --> 01:13:16.320
That's a great one.

01:13:16.320 --> 01:13:18.900
So, the sounds of being in a
bamboo forest and the sound

01:13:18.900 --> 01:13:23.240
of going from one place to
another in Burundi did you say?

01:13:23.240 --> 01:13:24.710
&gt;&gt; No this was Rwanda.

01:13:24.710 --> 01:13:26.010
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Rwanda.

01:13:26.010 --> 01:13:27.310
Any others?

01:13:27.310 --> 01:13:28.610
Yeah.

01:13:28.610 --> 01:13:35.860
&gt;&gt; So, growing up we didn't
have central heat in the house

01:13:35.860 --> 01:13:39.640
so my dad split wood
for our woodstove

01:13:39.640 --> 01:13:43.280
and so he taught me how to
split from when I was really,

01:13:43.280 --> 01:13:48.240
really young and you can tell
when a mull hits a piece of wood

01:13:48.240 --> 01:13:50.690
where it's all the way through,

01:13:50.690 --> 01:13:53.620
the mull would just
kind of split it.

01:13:53.620 --> 01:13:54.980
He wouldn't be looking,

01:13:54.980 --> 01:13:58.430
but I could as I was practicing
he could tell me whether it was

01:13:58.430 --> 01:14:00.340
going to split or
not from the sound

01:14:00.340 --> 01:14:02.180
of a [inaudible]
from the outside.

01:14:02.180 --> 01:14:05.140
It hasn't really moved,
but you could hear this pop

01:14:05.140 --> 01:14:07.150
of the all the strands
releasing.

01:14:07.150 --> 01:14:09.090
So, I'm listening for that

01:14:09.090 --> 01:14:12.810
and hear him bring
the mull [inaudible].

01:14:12.810 --> 01:14:14.110
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: It's
a great sound,

01:14:14.110 --> 01:14:16.740
and as you're saying it I
love to split wood myself

01:14:16.740 --> 01:14:19.110
and like I'm hearing
it as you say it.

01:14:19.110 --> 01:14:22.060
And also, how many I'm
just so glad you mentioned

01:14:22.060 --> 01:14:26.180
that in particular, because how
many times are we being informed

01:14:26.180 --> 01:14:30.150
by sounds especially when
like with a car, you know,

01:14:30.150 --> 01:14:31.870
the first thing you'll be in
your car and something' s up.

01:14:31.870 --> 01:14:34.600
I don't know what it is,
maybe it's the brakes,

01:14:34.600 --> 01:14:37.520
maybe it's the engine, but
it's not sounding the way it's

01:14:37.520 --> 01:14:38.820
supposed to.

01:14:38.820 --> 01:14:42.260
I mean we're, it's one of the
things that inform us often

01:14:42.260 --> 01:14:48.590
when things are wrong or right,
you can hear it first as a clue.

01:14:48.590 --> 01:14:50.310
Any other?

01:14:50.310 --> 01:14:51.610
Yeah.

01:14:51.610 --> 01:14:55.930
&gt;&gt; Hi, you know, you presented
such rich soundscapes, you know,

01:14:55.930 --> 01:14:58.360
in all the places that you
have been and it's funny,

01:14:58.360 --> 01:15:02.400
but what I thought of
was this a few years ago,

01:15:02.400 --> 01:15:05.670
and I was like by myself
and I above a tree line

01:15:05.670 --> 01:15:10.460
in Central Colorado probably
about 11,000 feet high

01:15:10.460 --> 01:15:13.240
so we were above the tree
lines, so there were no trees

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:15.940
and you know I could
see, see all around me.

01:15:15.940 --> 01:15:21.350
There was a big horizon and
there was very, this one part

01:15:21.350 --> 01:15:25.070
of the sound environment was,
I mean, it was mostly quiet,

01:15:25.070 --> 01:15:28.590
but you could hear very
subtle movement of the air.

01:15:28.590 --> 01:15:29.890
It wasn't really a breeze.

01:15:29.890 --> 01:15:33.230
It was just kind of very
subtle movement of the air

01:15:33.230 --> 01:15:36.010
and then every now and
then there would be a sound

01:15:36.010 --> 01:15:39.630
of an animal doing
something or a bird

01:15:39.630 --> 01:15:42.790
that was mostly near silence,

01:15:42.790 --> 01:15:45.550
but still there was a
little sound there and it's

01:15:45.550 --> 01:15:48.920
so interesting to think about
the fact that, you know,

01:15:48.920 --> 01:15:51.430
when we go through everyday
life, I mean, I think one thing

01:15:51.430 --> 01:15:54.740
about everyday life in the city
and now everywhere there's a lot

01:15:54.740 --> 01:15:57.090
of kind of manufactured sounds

01:15:57.090 --> 01:16:00.220
like you have a soundtrack
every time you go shopping or go

01:16:00.220 --> 01:16:03.410
into a restaurant or something,
and so [audio cuts out] same

01:16:03.410 --> 01:16:06.250
when you're in an environment
where you can when there's not,

01:16:06.250 --> 01:16:09.650
you know, a cacophony
of sound but there are,

01:16:09.650 --> 01:16:12.650
there's still subtle sound
going on and then every now

01:16:12.650 --> 01:16:15.530
and then more characteristic
sounds.

01:16:15.530 --> 01:16:16.830
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yes.

01:16:16.830 --> 01:16:20.140
That's so helpful, because then
in a place like that which,

01:16:20.140 --> 01:16:22.070
you know, it's relatively rare,

01:16:22.070 --> 01:16:26.630
certainly in the city except
maybe in the morning in cities

01:16:26.630 --> 01:16:30.760
or late at night, but even
so there's the sound that web

01:16:30.760 --> 01:16:33.140
of traffic going all the time.

01:16:33.140 --> 01:16:35.360
Without that you become
more finely attuned

01:16:35.360 --> 01:16:36.660
and more sensitized.

01:16:36.660 --> 01:16:38.630
I think that's a great example.

01:16:38.630 --> 01:16:43.320
Thank you, of a possibility
of hearing things

01:16:43.320 --> 01:16:45.930
that we don't always
necessarily hear.

01:16:45.930 --> 01:16:47.830
Any others?

01:16:47.830 --> 01:16:49.130
Yeah.

01:16:49.130 --> 01:16:51.900
&gt;&gt; So, I used to be
stationed in [inaudible].

01:16:51.900 --> 01:16:53.200
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: I'm sorry.

01:16:53.200 --> 01:16:54.500
Just a little louder.

01:16:54.500 --> 01:16:55.800
&gt;&gt; I used to be stationed

01:16:55.800 --> 01:16:57.610
at a naval air station
in Jacksonville.

01:16:57.610 --> 01:16:58.910
[Inaudible] medical
side I used to help

01:16:58.910 --> 01:17:04.050
out in [inaudible]
especially at night.

01:17:04.050 --> 01:17:05.780
I remember just [coughing] one

01:17:05.780 --> 01:17:09.870
of the hangers it was the last
plane of the night coming in

01:17:09.870 --> 01:17:13.810
and once it came in and the
engine shut off there's an

01:17:13.810 --> 01:17:17.180
extreme loudness
then extreme quiet.

01:17:17.180 --> 01:17:19.160
You could hear this cicadas
outside and the crickets

01:17:19.160 --> 01:17:22.430
and it was just that sudden
switch and [audio cuts out]

01:17:22.430 --> 01:17:24.730
and it was so loud you
couldn't hear anything

01:17:24.730 --> 01:17:27.200
and then so quiet you could.

01:17:27.200 --> 01:17:29.160
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Huh, great.

01:17:29.160 --> 01:17:33.310
Did, there was a moment like
that in the piece did that sort

01:17:33.310 --> 01:17:34.610
of trigger the memory?

01:17:34.610 --> 01:17:37.130
Huh. Cool.

01:17:37.130 --> 01:17:38.430
Any others?

01:17:38.430 --> 01:17:39.730
Yeah.

01:17:39.730 --> 01:17:42.470
&gt;&gt; After the riots in
Baltimore three years ago,

01:17:42.470 --> 01:17:46.120
[inaudible] who made it to that
baseball game with no crowd

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:49.100
in attendance, so
we would some of us

01:17:49.100 --> 01:17:51.290
who were season ticket
holders were used to the noise,

01:17:51.290 --> 01:17:55.150
the cacophony, the constant
mirage of jumbo trons

01:17:55.150 --> 01:17:58.310
and hotdog races and
all this nonsense

01:17:58.310 --> 01:18:02.120
and you could go stand the
outside of the stadium in some

01:18:02.120 --> 01:18:04.760
of the public accessible
places that listen

01:18:04.760 --> 01:18:09.010
to professional baseball game
being played with no crowd noise

01:18:09.010 --> 01:18:11.780
and no PA and no announcers.

01:18:11.780 --> 01:18:13.080
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Wow.

01:18:13.080 --> 01:18:15.010
Twilight zone.

01:18:15.010 --> 01:18:20.170
&gt;&gt; And Orioles catcher
actually came out and then

01:18:20.170 --> 01:18:24.330
to gage batting practice and
he waved to [inaudible] crowd.

01:18:24.330 --> 01:18:26.050
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Well, it's
also you're reminding me

01:18:26.050 --> 01:18:27.980
that it's another one of
those sounds, a wooden sound,

01:18:27.980 --> 01:18:30.040
but you talk to an outfielder

01:18:30.040 --> 01:18:32.900
and I have interviewed
outfielders or baseball players

01:18:32.900 --> 01:18:34.540
and they can tell by
the crack of a bat.

01:18:34.540 --> 01:18:37.000
It's one of the things that
informs them, well is it going

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:40.210
to be like a line drive,
aside from the visual,

01:18:40.210 --> 01:18:42.460
they hear that sound and
they know it's going to,

01:18:42.460 --> 01:18:43.760
oh it's a high pop or whatever.

01:18:43.760 --> 01:18:45.060
It's one of those things

01:18:45.060 --> 01:18:47.860
that has a different
sound quality of sound.

01:18:47.860 --> 01:18:49.160
Yeah, Tom.

01:18:49.160 --> 01:18:53.080
&gt;&gt; When I was very young,
we lived on a street

01:18:53.080 --> 01:18:55.360
that had a park at
the end of the block

01:18:55.360 --> 01:18:57.650
and every Saturday morning

01:18:57.650 --> 01:19:02.170
in the fall the local high
school marching band would go

01:19:02.170 --> 01:19:04.860
past my window on the
way to the football game

01:19:04.860 --> 01:19:06.970
and so I would wake up I
would hear the distance sound

01:19:06.970 --> 01:19:09.930
and they played out of tune,
because they weren't very good.

01:19:09.930 --> 01:19:11.230
It would get louder and louder.

01:19:11.230 --> 01:19:13.450
It was something like a
Doppler shift I guess,

01:19:13.450 --> 01:19:18.050
but with volume instead of and I
always knew when they were right

01:19:18.050 --> 01:19:20.230
in front of the house
it would pick up

01:19:20.230 --> 01:19:23.820
and then it would slowly fade
out as they would come pass.

01:19:23.820 --> 01:19:25.730
I always remembered that.

01:19:25.730 --> 01:19:27.900
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yeah,
It sounds emotion, yeah.

01:19:27.900 --> 01:19:32.180
&gt;&gt; I have a very similar one
actually it's a marching band

01:19:32.180 --> 01:19:36.570
one, It's from Minneapolis a
few years ago I was on a run

01:19:36.570 --> 01:19:41.710
and I stumbled on I guess it
was like, like the meeting time

01:19:41.710 --> 01:19:44.240
for a competition of marching
bands [audio cuts out].

01:19:44.240 --> 01:19:48.730
So, I was moving with
the marching band.

01:19:48.730 --> 01:19:50.650
They were all stationary
and they were in the bubble

01:19:50.650 --> 01:19:53.200
so I was running
through basically a field

01:19:53.200 --> 01:19:56.330
of marching bands
practicing with the big band.

01:19:56.330 --> 01:19:57.630
They all [inaudible].

01:19:57.630 --> 01:20:01.030
I tried to record it, I'm not
very good with sound recorders,

01:20:01.030 --> 01:20:04.040
but something about that
[audio cuts out] capture.

01:20:04.040 --> 01:20:05.860
I wanted to share another one.

01:20:05.860 --> 01:20:07.160
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Please,
please go on.

01:20:07.160 --> 01:20:09.520
&gt;&gt; When I was, I was brought
at my grandparent's house

01:20:09.520 --> 01:20:11.620
and always wanted to
walk to a sand hill.

01:20:11.620 --> 01:20:16.020
We called it a sand hill,
but you know there were a lot

01:20:16.020 --> 01:20:19.090
of small pebbles
[audio cuts out] sister

01:20:19.090 --> 01:20:23.830
and I would make piles and
we'd spend you know an hour

01:20:23.830 --> 01:20:28.660
or two throwing rocks down
the sand hill, so the sound

01:20:28.660 --> 01:20:30.160
of rocks [audio cuts out].

01:20:30.160 --> 01:20:35.780
And I haven't even mentioned,
you know, until you're talk

01:20:35.780 --> 01:20:38.270
on listening to some
of the sounds,

01:20:38.270 --> 01:20:44.250
but I live in a modest area now
and after the evening prayer,

01:20:44.250 --> 01:20:49.050
there's usually like a period
of meditation and we had

01:20:49.050 --> 01:20:53.730
to go break the silence with
small stone that he cracks

01:20:53.730 --> 01:20:57.480
against the pews when
they sit [audio cuts out].

01:20:57.480 --> 01:20:59.610
I've always found
it very pleasant

01:20:59.610 --> 01:21:03.560
and it's strange you know why
I thought that was so pleasant

01:21:03.560 --> 01:21:07.050
and I look forward to it.

01:21:07.050 --> 01:21:11.000
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Can you say what
kind of monastery it is, which?

01:21:11.000 --> 01:21:12.300
&gt;&gt; Yeah, Benedictine.

01:21:12.300 --> 01:21:13.860
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Benedictine.

01:21:13.860 --> 01:21:16.150
&gt;&gt; Say it sometimes.

01:21:16.150 --> 01:21:17.570
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: In, I
think Saint Benedicts said

01:21:17.570 --> 01:21:20.640
"Incline thy heart's ear"
is one of the things he said

01:21:20.640 --> 01:21:23.080
and so chanting, do you chant?

01:21:23.080 --> 01:21:24.380
&gt;&gt; No, we [inaudible].

01:21:24.380 --> 01:21:26.890
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Well, that
then when I was mentioning

01:21:26.890 --> 01:21:31.300
about Tomatis before, he was
a Alfred Tomatis was famously

01:21:31.300 --> 01:21:36.040
called to a group of
Benedictines monastery

01:21:36.040 --> 01:21:38.520
where all the, where they had
stopped, somebody had seemed

01:21:38.520 --> 01:21:41.560
like a good idea at the time
that they would stop chanting

01:21:41.560 --> 01:21:44.150
and have more time
for other stuff

01:21:44.150 --> 01:21:47.420
and in his words he found
them in their cells "lying

01:21:47.420 --> 01:21:51.210
like a bunch of limp dish rags",
that was his description of it

01:21:51.210 --> 01:21:56.580
and he basically his remedy
was to get them chanting again

01:21:56.580 --> 01:22:01.230
and that energized the sound
of the chant which he went

01:22:01.230 --> 01:22:03.420
on to thinking that that
particular frequency

01:22:03.420 --> 01:22:05.720
which is heard in the
middle of Gregorian chant

01:22:05.720 --> 01:22:09.870
which about one K, one
thousand cycles per second.

01:22:09.870 --> 01:22:13.590
He felt energized the brain.

01:22:13.590 --> 01:22:15.460
Now, I don't know if
that's true or not.

01:22:15.460 --> 01:22:17.210
He also felt Mozart
in particular,

01:22:17.210 --> 01:22:20.160
the music of Mozart was
prominent in those frequencies,

01:22:20.160 --> 01:22:25.060
but that, that quality
of music he felt helped,

01:22:25.060 --> 01:22:26.940
well as he put it,
"Energized the brain"

01:22:26.940 --> 01:22:29.550
which is an interesting
idea and he also felt

01:22:29.550 --> 01:22:31.350
that there were certain
kinds of sounds in music

01:22:31.350 --> 01:22:33.780
that did the opposite.

01:22:33.780 --> 01:22:38.060
So, luck you to be in the midst
of that sound environment.

01:22:38.060 --> 01:22:40.950
And a lot, so many
traditions have that sound

01:22:40.950 --> 01:22:45.580
in Greek orthodox
there's a sound of a,

01:22:45.580 --> 01:22:48.530
it has a particular name
which I've forgotten,

01:22:48.530 --> 01:22:53.600
but it's also the sound of
you know hitting something

01:22:53.600 --> 01:22:57.120
and then getting more rapidly.

01:22:57.120 --> 01:22:58.650
Any others?

01:22:58.650 --> 01:23:05.080
&gt;&gt; Just because I
have now been saved.

01:23:05.080 --> 01:23:06.380
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yeah.

01:23:06.380 --> 01:23:11.860
&gt;&gt; I find the many sounds
of water [audio cuts out].

01:23:11.860 --> 01:23:15.830
The rain starts to be heard.

01:23:15.830 --> 01:23:17.130
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yes.

01:23:17.130 --> 01:23:18.430
&gt;&gt; On the roof.

01:23:18.430 --> 01:23:19.730
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: Yeah.

01:23:19.730 --> 01:23:26.010
&gt;&gt; Or it may be a stream,
[inaudible] of the beach before.

01:23:26.010 --> 01:23:37.510
It has the way of bringing
me this impression of nature.

01:23:37.510 --> 01:23:42.530
[ Inaudible ]

01:23:42.530 --> 01:23:44.330
&gt;&gt; Jim Metzner: And we
are touched by the sounds

01:23:44.330 --> 01:23:45.850
of water and, in
fact, that was one

01:23:45.850 --> 01:23:47.270
of the sound memories
you don't hear it,

01:23:47.270 --> 01:23:50.150
but it was the last one
there was rain on the roof

01:23:50.150 --> 01:23:54.030
of a tin roof and many, many
people had mentioned that

01:23:54.030 --> 01:23:55.900
and if we listen to the end

01:23:55.900 --> 01:23:57.500
of the piece you would
hear somebody talking

01:23:57.500 --> 01:24:00.760
about that sound memory he
had of a very particular place

01:24:00.760 --> 01:24:02.840
and the evocative
sound of water.

01:24:02.840 --> 01:24:04.560
So, absolutely.

01:24:04.560 --> 01:24:10.090
So, we live in a world of
vibration that we mostly take

01:24:10.090 --> 01:24:14.610
for granted and we also carry
within us this inner archive

01:24:14.610 --> 01:24:18.370
of sounds and complete with all

01:24:18.370 --> 01:24:22.740
of the associated relentless
associations that come with them

01:24:22.740 --> 01:24:26.650
and somehow our lives are lived

01:24:26.650 --> 01:24:30.760
between these two
realms of sound.

01:24:30.760 --> 01:24:34.460
The outer and the inner and this

01:24:34.460 --> 01:24:39.260
in between place is
a little mysterious,

01:24:39.260 --> 01:24:45.230
it's a little unknown,
it's quiet, it's still,

01:24:45.230 --> 01:24:49.220
it's sensitive, it's a
bit like being in the eye

01:24:49.220 --> 01:24:53.730
of a storm attuning to
something very subtle.

01:24:53.730 --> 01:24:59.450
It may be a vibration
that is more sensed

01:24:59.450 --> 01:25:02.710
than felt than heard.

01:25:03.740 --> 01:25:06.090
It's like if you've
ever had the experience

01:25:06.090 --> 01:25:09.890
of someone asking
a question and all

01:25:09.890 --> 01:25:12.940
of a sudden you're
hearing the question

01:25:12.940 --> 01:25:14.910
that was behind that question.

01:25:14.910 --> 01:25:16.210
Do you know what I mean?

01:25:16.210 --> 01:25:17.690
Not the words that came
out of their mouth,

01:25:17.690 --> 01:25:19.290
but you're hearing what was,

01:25:19.290 --> 01:25:21.620
what inspired them
to ask that question.

01:25:21.620 --> 01:25:23.060
Do you know what I mean?

01:25:23.060 --> 01:25:27.870
Sometimes it's like an intuition
and that's I think similar

01:25:27.870 --> 01:25:30.350
to what we're speaking about,

01:25:30.350 --> 01:25:35.830
the idea that whenever
we're listening attentively,

01:25:35.830 --> 01:25:38.990
we have the possibility
not only of being nourished

01:25:38.990 --> 01:25:46.040
by this swirling microcosmic
galaxy of sounds and vibrations,

01:25:46.040 --> 01:25:50.650
but also what lies behind them.

01:25:50.650 --> 01:25:53.910
So, the thought I'd like
to leave you with is

01:25:53.910 --> 01:25:59.960
that by becoming quiet
enough inside, perhaps it's

01:25:59.960 --> 01:26:03.160
in that realm that
we can become,

01:26:03.160 --> 01:26:07.430
we can rediscover the
magic of listening.

01:26:07.430 --> 01:26:09.510
Thank you.

01:26:09.510 --> 01:26:21.350
